title: For Sale:  WWII Vet Bring-Back Browning 1910 w/Capture Papers & Holster
postcontent: I have, for sale, a Browning model 1910 pistol that was brought back from Germany in WWII.  It is chambered in .32acp.  I have the original capture papers and holster for it.  It is in rough shape as can be seen in the pictures.  There are no Nazi markings on the gun that I can see.  There is heavy pitting on the slide from where it sat in the holster.  "Navy" is marked on the back of the capture paper, so more than likely the pitting is from while he was on his ship.  The bore is like a mirror with sharp rifling.  The action seems to function fine.  The holster was modified by the veteran to use as a shoulder holster.  It is marked "39" on the back which is likely the year it was made.  All in all it's a nice identified set with provenance.  Asking $400 or best reasonable offer.  I am located in Jeffersonville, Indiana.  Out of state residents must provide an FFL or C&R license before I ship it.  If you would like to see more pictures, let me know.  Thanks!

Massad Ayoob is internationally known as a renowned author, columnist, and instructor on the subject of firearms and self-defense. He is Glock Talk's resident expert in the GATE Self-Defense Forum. 

On several occasions, Ayoob has made very compelling and positive statements about the amazing accuracy of the G30 which he has chosen for one of his carry guns. Ayoob favors the G30 over the G21 and G36 Glock 45ACP pistols and calls the G30 his favorite Glock. In his book, "The Gun Digest Book of Combat Handgunnery", Ayoob writes the G30 "may be the most accurate pistol that Glock makes." In his personal experience, the stock G30 with factory ammo is capable of under 1.0-inch groups for 5 shots at 25 yards from off the bench, performing better than the Gen3 G21 or G36. The G30 is freakishly accurate for a combat pistol with a 3.78 inch barrel. 

"Mas wrote a comprehensive review of the Glock 30 that was published in the American Handgunner 1998 Combat Annual, titled "Fist Full of .45". The impressive result he obtained on the firing range with the first G30 he received for evaluation is very interesting reading. After firing three boxes of ammo to break in the pistol, Ayoob shot a 1-3/16" group of 5 shots at a measured range of 25 yards from a righthand barricade standing position using Federal 230gr HydraShok HP factory ammo. The best three of five shots were just 3/8" apart. He was so favorably impressed by the G30 that he couldn't resist the temptation to buy the test pistol for his personal use."
